<fr:p>Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\prod  X_\alpha ]]></fr:tex> be a <fr:link
type="local"
href="rs-002S.xml"
addr="rs-002S"
title="Cartesian product of sets">product</fr:link> of a family of
<fr:link
type="local"
href="rs-00CA.xml"
addr="rs-00CA"
title="Topological space">spaces</fr:link> <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[X_\alpha ]]></fr:tex>. Then the
<fr:em>product topology</fr:em> on <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\prod  X_\alpha ]]></fr:tex> is the <fr:link
type="local"
href="rs-00CN.xml"
addr="rs-00CN"
title="Characterization of (co)limits in Top">initial topology</fr:link> with
respect to the projections <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\prod  X_\alpha \xrightarrow {\pi _\beta } X_\beta ]]></fr:tex>. It thus
has the following universal property: a <fr:link
type="local"
href="rs-005M.xml"
addr="rs-005M"
title="Set-function">set-function</fr:link>
<fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[Z\xrightarrow {f} \prod  X_\alpha ]]></fr:tex> is <fr:link
type="local"
href="rs-00CD.xml"
addr="rs-00CD"
title="Continuous map">continuous</fr:link> if and only if each of
the composites <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[Z\xrightarrow {f} \prod  X_\alpha \xrightarrow {\pi _\beta } X_\beta ]]></fr:tex> are.</fr:p><fr:p>Explicitly, the product topology is <fr:link
type="local"
href="rs-00CL.xml"
addr="rs-00CL"
title="Base for a topology">generated by the base</fr:link>
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[\left \{\prod  U_\alpha : U_\alpha \subseteq  X_\alpha  \text { open and } U_\alpha  = X_\alpha  \text { for all but finitely many }\alpha .\right \}]]></fr:tex></fr:p><fr:p>The point is that the initial topology is generated by the
<fr:link
type="local"
href="rs-00CO.xml"
addr="rs-00CO"
title="Subbase for a topology">subbase</fr:link> of preimages of open sets under the projections, and we only
take finite intersections of these, hence the finite support of the <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[U_\alpha ]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree><fr:tree
